              ]
            },
            "answerKey": {
              "assessmentType": "multiplechoice",
              "answers": {
                "answer_3": {
                  "score": 0.0,
                  "response": "sider this: We gain social status from the family we are in but those statuses do not give us an account of the people we are related to. LO 4.2 Explain the significance of social structure and its components: culture, social class, social status, roles, groups, and social institutions; compare the functionalist and conflict perspectives on social structure; and explain what holds society together."
                },
                "answer_2": {
                  "score": 0.0,
                  "response": "sider this: While we share norms, values, behaviors, and other social bonds with our family, these shared elements do not give us an account of the people we are related to. LO 4.2 Explain the significance of social structure and its components: culture, social class, social status, roles, groups, and social institutions; compare the functionalist and conflict perspectives on social structure; and explain what holds society together."
                },
                "answer_1": {
                  "score": 0.0,
                  "response": "sider this: In the U.S. we use a bilineal system of descent in which we track our heritage through both our mother and father’s side of the family. LO 4.2 Explain the significance of social structure and its components: culture, social class, social status, roles, groups, and social institutions; compare the functionalist and conflict perspectives on social structure; and explain what holds society together."
                },
                "answer_4": {
                  "score": 1.0,
                  "response": "That’s correct!"
                }
              }
            },
